Company Description


Guild Investment Management is a global value manager. The firm seeks to identify opportunities for capital appreciation and income through investments in: the stocks of US and non-US companies; ETFs and index shares of US markets and commodities;  foreign currency deposits or forwards; and other foreign currency denominated securities including bonds, cash equivalents, index shares or derivatives instruments.Guild examines the global markets to identify macroeconomic and sociopolitical or demographic changes or trends that provide opportunities in countries, sectors, industries and companies. Once they have identified these opportunities, Guild employs bottom-up, fundamental research on target companies to determine their potential for appreciation.  The firm prefers to invest in the stocks of undervalued companies that are operating in growing industries. They look for companies that are trading at p/e ratios below their expected percentage rate of earnings growth. Guild looks for companies that have fallen in price or are under appreciated due to a stock market decline that leaves the stock of a growing company cheaper, on a statistical basis, than its mean valuation over the past 10 years. They also look for an industry group or sector-related decline in price due to cyclical reasons or due to market perceptions about a specific industry that they believe may be temporary.Guild provides active portfolio management. The firm does not believe that portfolios must be fully invested in stocks at all times. They look for opportunities with favorable reward/risk parameters. The firm employs an opportunistic style that is responsive to changes in the markets. Guild continuously reevaluates the asset allocations and positions in their portfolios. When opportunities arise, Guild utilizes foreign currencies and foreign currency denominated cash equivalents to earn income and to capture appreciation from foreign exchange trends. The firm also looks for investments that offer the potential to appreciate 50% in 12 months and that have a perceived reward/risk potential of 3 to 1.




